  "conclusions": [
    "hipENGINE now beats llama.cpp HIP on decode at both accepted shapes and beats it strongly on 4K prefill; 4K derived total time is about 15% lower than llama.cpp HIP.",
    "hipENGINE beats llama.cpp Vulkan on prefill at both accepted shapes, and the 4K derived total time is lower because prefill dominates enough to offset Vulkan decode; Vulkan still has much faster short/medium decode.",
    "hipENGINE is close to the PARO source-lineage 4K target on prefill (-1.5%) but remains behind PARO decode (-14.2%) and short-context prefill/decode (-20.6%/-23.0%).",
    "The next performance focus should be Q8_0 T16 GEMV decode, especially the redundant per-lane T16 scale load/broadcast opportunity, before returning to selected-MoE T16 or RMSNorm/router launch cleanup.",
    "Do not spend the next pass on attention split-K: post-D10 profiling shows full_attention_decode is now only about 10% of 4K decode kernel time."
  ],
  "recommended_next_order": [
    "P10.D11: Q8_0 T16 GEMV scale-load/broadcast polish and split-output dense/shared GEMV audit; target the 35.45% decode bucket.",
    "P10.D12: selected-MoE T16 GEMV revisit only after Q8_0 bucket shrinks; combined Q4/Q5 selected buckets are about 21.44% of 4K decode kernel time.",
    "P10.D13: short-context split-K threshold=512 numeric fixture; only retain if split-vs-context outputs pass tolerance and token stream concern is explained.",
    "P10.M0: memory-context pass for accepted 32K/128 and 128K/128 capability, because llama.cpp/PARO have long-context rows while hipENGINE current accepted rollup stops at 4K and 128K preflight is blocked."
